vectorData.altText: 1. What is the target of somatic motor fibres?
That's right!  Somatic motor fibres are defined by their target. They innervate voluntary (skeletal or striated) muscle.
That is incorrect. Click here      to learn the answer, then come back to try again.

Functionally, the nervous system is subdivided into the somatic and visceral (autonomic) nervous systems.
These subdivisions are defined by their targets.
Somatic      nervous system SoNS
this subdivision innervates the body wall, limbs, and much of the neck and extracranial      structures
its motor component controls skeletal (voluntary) muscle in these body regions
its sensory component monitors receptors  in these body regions
Autonomic      nervous system ANS
this subdivision innervates viscera     and glands
its motor component controls smooth (involuntary) muscle (found in viscera other than the heart), cardiac      muscle (found only in the heart) and glands, 
its sensory component monitors the activity and health of visceral organs
1.2   Functional Subdivisions of the Nervous System
internal organs, e.g. stomach, lungs, heart, etc.
Extracranial structures are those of the head that are external to the skull.
